================================================================
PRACTICAL 8(c) - Install and Automate Using UiPath Plugins
================================================================

DIFFICULTY: Hard (covers 7 plugins)

WHAT YOU WILL DO:
Demonstrate automation using 7 plugins:
Mail, PDF, Excel, Word, Web, Java, Credential Management

--- PLUGIN INSTALLATION ---

Step 1: In UiPath Studio → click "Manage Packages" (top ribbon).
  - Search and install each of these:
    * UiPath.Mail.Activities
    * UiPath.PDF.Activities
    * UiPath.Excel.Activities  (likely already installed)
    * UiPath.Word.Activities
    * UiPath.WebAPI.Activities
  - For Java Plugin: UiPath Studio → Tools → Java Extension → Install
  - Click Save after installing.

Step 2: Open UiPath Studio → New Project.
  - Name it: Practical_8c_Plugins

--- MAIL PLUGIN ---

Step 3: From Activities, drag "Send SMTP Mail Message".
  - To: "yourtestemail@gmail.com"
  - Subject: "Test from UiPath"
  - Body: "Hello, this email was sent by UiPath automation."
  - SMTPServer: "smtp.gmail.com"
  - Port: 587
  - EnableSSL: True
  - Username: "yourgmail@gmail.com"
  - Password: "your_app_password"
    (Note: Use a Gmail App Password — go to myaccount.google.com → Security → App Passwords)
  - Run (F5) → check your email inbox.

--- PDF PLUGIN ---

Step 4: Create a sample PDF or download any PDF file. 
  Save it as "sample.pdf" on Desktop.

Step 5: From Activities, drag "Read PDF Text" activity.
  - FileName: "C:\Users\YourName\Desktop\sample.pdf"
  - Output → Text: press Ctrl+K → name it: pdfText

Step 6: Drag a "Message Box" → Text: pdfText
  - Run (F5) → see the extracted PDF text.

--- EXCEL PLUGIN ---

Step 7: (Already covered in Practical 6 — refer to those steps)
  Quick demo: Use "Excel Application Scope" + "Read Range" + "Message Box".

--- WORD PLUGIN ---

Step 8: Create a sample Word document. Type some text. Save as "doc1.docx".

Step 9: From Activities, drag "Word Application Scope".
  - FilePath: "C:\Users\YourName\Desktop\doc1.docx"

Step 10: Inside Word Application Scope, drag "Read Text" activity.
  - Output → Text: press Ctrl+K → name it: wordText

Step 11: Drag Message Box after the scope → Text: wordText
  - Run (F5) → the text from your Word file is shown.

--- WEB INTEGRATION ---

Step 12: Open Chrome browser → navigate to https://example.com

Step 13: Drag an "Open Browser" activity (or use Attach Browser 
         if already open).
  - URL: "https://example.com"
  - BrowserType: Chrome

Step 14: Inside Open Browser, drag "Get Text" activity.
  - Indicate element on screen → click the heading text on example.com
  - Output → Ctrl+K → name it: webText

Step 15: Drag Message Box → Text: webText
  - Run (F5) → extracts text from the webpage.

--- JAVA PLUGIN ---

Step 16: Install UiPath Java Extension:
  - UiPath Studio → Tools → Java Extension → Install
  - Restart Studio.

Step 17: Open any Java application on your computer 
  (or use a simple Java Swing app if available).
  - UiPath can now interact with Java application UI elements 
    the same way it interacts with Windows apps.
  - Use "Click", "Type Into", "Get Text" activities — they will 
    now work on Java apps too after extension is installed.

--- CREDENTIAL MANAGEMENT ---

Step 18: To securely store credentials:
  - Open Windows Credential Manager 
    (Windows Search → "Credential Manager" → Windows Credentials)
  - Click "Add a generic credential"
    Internet/network address: "MyAppLogin"
    Username: "testuser"
    Password: "testpassword"
  - Click OK.

Step 19: In UiPath, drag "Get Secure Credential" activity.
  - Target: "MyAppLogin"
  - Output → Username: press Ctrl+K → name it: storedUser
  - Output → Password: press Ctrl+K → name it: storedPass

Step 20: Drag "Message Box" → Text: storedUser
  - Run (F5) → UiPath retrieves the stored username securely.
  - The password is retrieved as SecureString (never shown in plain text).

================================================================
EXTRA NOTES FOR PRACTICAL 8:
================================================================
- Events are used to REACT to user actions — they don't click themselves.
  They listen and then trigger your automation workflow.
- Screen Scraping Wizard is the easiest way to use Full Text/Native/OCR.
  Access it from the top Design ribbon in UiPath Studio.
- Full Text is fast but may grab hidden text. Native is cleaner.
  Use OCR only when the other two don't work (e.g., on images).
- For Mail Plugin, Gmail requires an App Password (not your normal password)
  if 2FA is enabled. Create one at myaccount.google.com → Security.
- Credential Management is important for secure automation — 
  NEVER hardcode passwords directly in your workflow.
